Particularly useful with multiple owners that update same plan. Committing changes can be problematic since the changes can be done by multiple people and you cannot determine which changes I made.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Portfolio Cloud*. Using *JIRA Portfolio Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JPOSERVER-1634].
  {panel}

We primarily look at our future plans in terms of releases. Epics cross releases. Stories are very granular.

Please add an option to show Releases in the dropdown for Epics and Stories so the Releases show up on the Gantt. This would create a nice timeline view for the releases. 

I realize that Releases are different objects than epics and stories and this may present trouble for this solution. Alternate ways to get at the same type of view would be useful if it cannot be incorporated into the main page.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Portfolio Cloud*. Using *JIRA Portfolio Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JPOSERVER-1652].
  {panel}

It would reduce manual updates if the assignee from JIRA populates the member filed in Portfolio and in turn identifies the existing team that person is a member of and populates. 

It could throw and error when this cannot be done.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Portfolio Cloud*. Using *JIRA Portfolio Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JPOSERVER-1558].
  {panel}

It can be easy to miss scheduling errors/warnings if the parent issue is collapsed. It would be good if the parent issues also had an icon next to them (perhaps slightly transparent) if one of their children has an error.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Portfolio Cloud*. Using *JIRA Portfolio Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JPOSERVER-1573].
  {panel}

I use Portfolio more for seeing an elegant hierarchy view on a single screen for the status of a particular release, because no other view in JIRA is as useful for doing this (from what I've found in my many years of living Atlassian). A very small amount of time do I use Portfolio to actually do forecasting.

What prevents this from working well for me is that Portfolio will not inherit the assignee from the issue in the view until an estimate value is set for each item.

Can there be an option to inherit the assignee of the issue and show it without requiring an estimate?

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Portfolio Cloud*. Using *JIRA Portfolio Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JPOSERVER-1835].
  {panel}

From a support request:

{quote}
What we would like is a flexible way to report total hours logged on all child issues of an Initiative. For example: How many hours were logged on Initiative X in January, February, etc. This would include all Epics linked to the Initiative (via the parent link field), User Stories within the epic, and sub-tasks linked to User Stories.

Portfolio does have a way to report this [via the progress pop-up in Portfolio itself|https://confluence.atlassian.com/jiraportfoliocloud/tracking-progress-and-status-828785247.html], but we would like to automate our reporting.
{quote}

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Portfolio Cloud*. Using *JIRA Portfolio Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JPOSERVER-1440].
  {panel}

I would like to be able to export the Gantt chart created by the Portfolio plugin so that I can re-use the graphic overview for other purposes (eg in Powerpoint). Currently, I can only do so using a screenshot. It would be great to be able to export to a file format like Excel or MS Project so that after export I can than further optimise the gantt chart  for presentation purposes. Having said that, a simple PDF export would be a nice first step.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Portfolio Cloud*. Using *JIRA Portfolio Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JPOSERVER-1303].
  {panel}

Schedule algorithm currently ignores story assignee.  When using Live Plans to show a roll up of multiple existing Agile boards, it would be useful to have the assignee on stories used for scheduling.  This is especially true of the story has no sub-tasks.

This would address "grouping be person" issue reported in JPO-1290

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Portfolio Cloud*. Using *JIRA Portfolio Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JPOSERVER-1295].
  {panel}

Exporting the plan to a PDF would be incredibly helpful.

Often plans need to be sent to external customers/sponsors who are not always allowed direct access to the Jira or Portfolio pages. In these cases it would be helpful to have a PDF export option to transmit this schedule to those players.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Portfolio Cloud*. Using *JIRA Portfolio Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JPOSERVER-1723].
  {panel}

Need to be able to find all issues not linked to a team in JQL

Not only to find those "managed" by Portfolio and not properly linked but most importantly to find those NOT managed by Portfolio

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Portfolio Cloud*. Using *JIRA Portfolio Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JPOSERVER-1730].
  {panel}

Right now tickets are all going into whatever the next release is in order. For some projects that makes sense. For some it doesn't. Is there a way to tell Portfolio when its Calculating the release to use to default to Later instead of looking at the list of releases? I'm getting Releases with dates that are shifting, not because of the already scheduled items, but because of new items that should never have been assigned to that release.

 

See mockup.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Portfolio Cloud*. Using *JIRA Portfolio Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JPOSERVER-1609].
  {panel}

Add a possibility to filter on empty or none to the filters on Release, Teams and Themes.
This makes it possible to find issues that do not have these fields filled in.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Portfolio Cloud*. Using *JIRA Portfolio Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JPOSERVER-1703].
  {panel}

It would be nice, if in Portfolio, you had the ability to specify which stages/skills apply to which project or even issues

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Portfolio Cloud*. Using *JIRA Portfolio Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JPOSERVER-1722].
  {panel}

Need to be able to find all issues not linked to a parent in JQL

Not only to find those "managed" by Portfolio and not properly linked but most importantly to find those NOT managed by Portfolio

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Portfolio Cloud*. Using *JIRA Portfolio Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JPOSERVER-514].
  {panel}

The only way to currently articulate wait time between tasks is to hard code in a earliest start date to an estimate. We have a lot of tasks that involve waiting for other items to be finished or that need to be rendered on the chart but don't need dynamic duration calculations. Two examples of this are:
- We have to make a large capital purchase, there is work that precedes the purchase and follows after the capital arrives at our facility but there is not a good way to block out this lag while waiting on external vendors. If we use the earliest start date then this may become inaccurate if the preceding task's estimate changes.
- We have an operational group that is doing work but don't reflect their work in JIRA - we would like to be able to render the work as a bar on the gantt chart but tracking status and allocating resources is a pain. Creating virtual users and virtual teams is a possibility but fairly cumbersome in it's current incarnation so we really just want to be able to render an epic with a fixed amount of time without resources being allocated to it and it dynamically changing.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Portfolio Cloud*. Using *JIRA Portfolio Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JPOSERVER-1352].
  {panel}

I may be missing something, but currently if I sort by the progress column in the Portfolio scope section, there doesn't seem to be a way to revert back to sorting on rank other than removing and re-adding the column I've sorted on.

It would be great if there was some obvious way to revert back to sorting on rank, this is causing confusion for users as they can no longer reprioritise their issues and it's not clear why.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Portfolio Cloud*. Using *JIRA Portfolio Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JPOSERVER-1253].
  {panel}

*Problem:*
When a user adds stories to an epic, i.e., changes the epic from unstructured to structured, the epic loses its estimates. The first child inherits this estimate and subsequently, the parent just displays the sum of its child estimates; it is no longer possible to set estimates on the parent element (which would then add to the sum of children). The same goes for adding epics to unstructured initiatives.

This is related to [this problem|https://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JPO-1234] where the original estimate on an unstructured epic gets lost as soon as child stories are added.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Portfolio Cloud*. Using *JIRA Portfolio Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JPOSERVER-1626].
  {panel}

Would really be helpful to be able to configure unique non-working day schedules per person and/or per team. That would make managing time off and global resources capacity so much easier than what is currently in place.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Portfolio Cloud*. Using *JIRA Portfolio Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JPOSERVER-1879].
  {panel}

As a project manager I need to include in the schedule also periodic activities, associated to a theme, to a team, to a state (just like any other story/epic).

For example, I need to schedule 2 days/week of Mike to do "onsite visit" to a client, and Mary 5d/month to do "training", etc.

I would like these activities to show up in the schedule and affect capacity.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
*NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Portfolio Cloud*. Using *JIRA Portfolio Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JPOSERVER-1885].
{panel}
With the new team field (via portfolio) a lot of our email filters would highly benefit by being able to sort by the team field contents.  As you are fully aware, JIRA tends to be very "chatty" with the amount of emails it sends and being able to filter and organize these emails are a must.

Can we please make this a default field moving forward.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Portfolio Cloud*. Using *JIRA Portfolio Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JPOSERVER-1427].
  {panel}

After creating a team it is not possible to change the avatar of a shared team. It would be nice to set a picture like the user or project avatars.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Portfolio Cloud*. Using *JIRA Portfolio Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JPOSERVER-1555].
  {panel}

h3. Problem Definition
Let's say, I have one issue PJA-1 - type Task that belongs to ProjectA and linked (relates to, clones, block, etc.) to multiple issues. This issue PJA-1 has been imported to Portfolio and the issue/issues that linked to it should show on issue details view in Portfolio. The actual result is not showing the issue/issues linked to PJA-1.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Portfolio Cloud*. Using *JIRA Portfolio Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JPOSERVER-1798].
  {panel}

Trying to use Portfolio, and the estimator is spreading our points across every possible skill on the team.  We are a small BI team, and so person A does ETL, person B does reporting, person C does analysis, etc.  Some stories require all, some stories only require one, and everything in between.

Would love to leverage something like components (or a like field) to have Portfolio know which skills to allocate across.  We look to set component as part of our backlog grooming effort so we know who we need estimates from.  SO this is part of our workflow and wouldn't require additional work.  But me doing it after the fact in Portfolio is tedious and frustrating.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Portfolio Cloud*. Using *JIRA Portfolio Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JPOSERVER-1607].
  {panel}

Love Portfolio!
However, the top blocker for us is the inability to have a Portfolio team be reflected into anything in Jira world. Having the ability to have a team map into anything which could be used in JQL (a component, a label, ...) would help tremendously.
End goal would be to associate a Jira board with a team in portfolio.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Portfolio Cloud*. Using *JIRA Portfolio Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JPOSERVER-1667].
  {panel}

I want to filter on the Team in Jira but don't see that as a field.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Portfolio Cloud*. Using *JIRA Portfolio Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JPOSERVER-1425].
  {panel}

At present, if multiple releases in a plan have release dates fixed to one date, only a the name of a single release is displayed on the schedule. We would like all releases to be listed, or an icon to expand indicating that there are additional releases on the date.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Portfolio Cloud*. Using *JIRA Portfolio Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JPOSERVER-1643].
  {panel}

It is important to be able to see the Story level, but it is difficult to understand the context of Stories because their respective Epic is not visible.

Enabling the user to set "Grouping" by Epic when viewing Reports > Schedule would help. 

This view is fundamental to the success of Portfolio. It is essential that after inserting and updating the raw data, that the user can then get a quality dashboard delivering a clear summary. A special Plan Dashboard view could also be required if this schedule view cannot manage it.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Portfolio Cloud*. Using *JIRA Portfolio Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JPOSERVER-1375].
  {panel}

Currently security has 'Administrators' and 'Read Only' users. Those that have administrators it would be useful to restrict those who have the ability to update the Portfolio plans from having the ability to push data/information back to JIRA (making it one directional).

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Portfolio Cloud*. Using *JIRA Portfolio Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JPOSERVER-1604].
  {panel}

Under Reports and Themes, have multiple settings where we can show percentages by issue count. Within issue count, allow us to multiple select the issue type. This is helpful for kanban teams that do not track time nor do story points.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Portfolio Cloud*. Using *JIRA Portfolio Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JPOSERVER-1329].
  {panel}

When the minimum load value for scheduling epics without child stories is set to a high enough value to prevent the epic from being scheduled, a "Planning horizon" warning is triggered.

It would be helpful to have a more detailed message that points the customer to that option.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Portfolio Cloud*. Using *JIRA Portfolio Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JPOSERVER-1470].
  {panel}

In Portfolio 1.0, people could not be shared between plans, but some people work on multiple projects. Therefore, the only workable method was to create one plan for all projects, then enter all users, skills, themes, initiatives, etc.

We would like to use the 2.0 features, but there is no means of importing/ upgrading/ converting the old data.

As users, we find "recreate all from scratch" to be too painful of an upgrade method.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Portfolio Cloud*. Using *JIRA Portfolio Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JPOSERVER-1552].
  {panel}

Sprints start date currently always start on "today". There should be a configuration that allow this to be customised per team.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Portfolio Cloud*. Using *JIRA Portfolio Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JPOSERVER-1265].
  {panel}

At the moment, the _Actual_ values on the reports page are always based on the time logged on the linked JIRA tickets, regardless of the Portfolio plan's estimation unit. This is fine for plans using hours or days. However, for plans using story points it would be preferable to compute the actuals based on the progress. That is, the story points of all items matching the active filter could be summed up and multiplied by the progress of these tickets. This value could then be distributed with respect to the _Themes_ configured for this plan.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Portfolio Cloud*. Using *JIRA Portfolio Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JPOSERVER-1751].
  {panel}

Currently the Team dropdown is alphabetized, but the Project dropdown isn't.  Seems like a minor enough thing, but when inline creating hundreds of epics, it makes a difference.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Portfolio Cloud*. Using *JIRA Portfolio Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JPOSERVER-1228].
  {panel}

As a user, I want to see the backlog icons for initiative, epic, and user stories so that I can easily distinguish the issue type in the list view.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Portfolio Cloud*. Using *JIRA Portfolio Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JPOSERVER-1357].
  {panel}

With the introduction of arbitrary issue hierarchies in Portfolio Live Plans, the way Portfolio stores its hierarchy information has changed. Whereas with standard plans, Initiative/Epic links were stored as _Issue Links_, this information is now stored as an _issue property_ that as of now is not visible in JIRA. That is, when you open your initiative in JIRA you do not see any information on the child epics. Only in case of Agile Epic / Story relationships this information is visible in JIRA since there is a dedicated custom field for this already, the _Epic Link_.

It would be great to make the hierarchy information used by Portfolio Live Plans visible in JIRA in a similar way as Epic/Story relationships of Agile / JIRA Software are visualized.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Portfolio Cloud*. Using *JIRA Portfolio Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JPOSERVER-1394].
  {panel}

At present there is no prompt to add a plan name when a plan is being created, once it's created it's just called "Untitled plan" unless the user remembers to change it.

This makes it hard for users to find their plans again if other people have also forgotten to name theirs, so we end up with multiple untitled plans. 

This would be resolved by making it mandatory to set a name for the plan - or even having a field during the wizard to prompt users to fill it in

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Portfolio Cloud*. Using *JIRA Portfolio Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JPOSERVER-1854].
  {panel}

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Portfolio Cloud*. Using *JIRA Portfolio Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JPOSERVER-1784].
  {panel}

Goal

Allow easier filtering/triage for reviewing items on the Scope tab (at a minimum) by letting you set a "Not Set / Empty" value for dates, Project, Release, Theme, Component, (or any other valid) options presented. 

This would help, for example, simplify ensuring that all work has a theme set to help use the pie chart report for planned vs actual time allocation by theme.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Portfolio Cloud*. Using *JIRA Portfolio Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JPOSERVER-510].
  {panel}

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Portfolio Cloud*. Using *JIRA Portfolio Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JPOSERVER-1838].
  {panel}

h3. Problem Definition
Currently, there is no report available for Epics in Portfolio

h3. Suggested Solution
The customer would like to have: 
{quote}
something like a bar chart, each bar represent an epic and has different color per status - green for # of done issues, yellow for in progress and blue for to do.
{quote}
 *  !Epic Report Portfolio.png|thumbnail! 

h3. Workaround 
The [Epic Report|https://confluence.atlassian.com/jirasoftwarecloud/epic-report-777002698.html] available in Jira Software might be helpful

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Portfolio Cloud*. Using *JIRA Portfolio Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JPOSERVER-1639].
  {panel}

I want to be able to use the 'parent link' system with Story and Task issue types. A Story is used as a user story (As a user, I want xxx). I have then Task issues that implement this story (I usually have different Tasks per platform (iOS, Android). I don't use sub-tasks because I want to developers to be able to split out their task into sub-tasks if need be. If I would use sub-tasks, this is not possible anymore.
I would like to view this hierarchy in portfolio as well of course.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Portfolio Cloud*. Using *JIRA Portfolio Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JPOSERVER-481].
  {panel}

For a PM it is very vital to observe shift in start dates, finish dates, durations, and work or labor estimates from the baselined plan (with original) in order to find out 'Finish Variance', 'Work Variance' (overruns occurred) so that corrective action could be taken to avoid delays.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Portfolio Cloud*. Using *JIRA Portfolio Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JPOSERVER-1374].
  {panel}

Having the ability to see the priority icon visible on the chart (even though there is limited retail space to view it) would provide a lot of value when viewing along with the current information.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Portfolio Cloud*. Using *JIRA Portfolio Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JPOSERVER-1229].
  {panel}

As a user, I want to see list of the user stories in my backlog so that I can prioritize the user stories.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Portfolio Cloud*. Using *JIRA Portfolio Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JPOSERVER-532].
  {panel}

Initiative is very useful in Portfolio but it would be really lovely to be able to use JIRA filters to query the same data, for presentation in Dashboards, exports, etc.
It would be great if you could create a custom field called Initiative in JIRA, when Portfolio pushes data back to JIRA it could update this custom field.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Portfolio Cloud*. Using *JIRA Portfolio Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JPOSERVER-1266].
  {panel}

Currently "Themes" view will only show effort distribution across predefined themes. What we are looking for is to be able to see progress/schedule for Themes (similar as we can see for Initiatives). 
This is very valuable for communicating development plans to the entities like Board of Directors, C* level executives and more. Initiatives view is great for planning, but already too granular for them.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Portfolio Cloud*. Using *JIRA Portfolio Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JPOSERVER-1692].
  {panel}

Currently, you have to choose whether you are viewing epics in a list with stories and defects underneath all of it or just stories themselves.  When dealing with a bigger portfolio sometimes it is helpful to align defects to epics and within your overall priority.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Portfolio Cloud*. Using *JIRA Portfolio Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JPOSERVER-1557].
  {panel}

Hi,

Currently, there are some columns in the timeline view of the scope tab that are not sortable.  It would be very useful to be able to sort the column that shows the warnings.  This way I can group all the warnings together and address them one by one instead of having to scroll and find each warnings among all records.  Screenshot attached.

Great improvements btw in Live Plans, we love it.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Portfolio Cloud*. Using *JIRA Portfolio Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JPOSERVER-1865].
  {panel}

As a Portfolio planner, I would like Portfolio to warn me if i am adding an issue to a Sprint that's already in progress so that I can be aware of the fact that I am pushing a scope change. 

 

Note: This may have to happen at commit time rather than the time that the Issue was assigned to a sprint in case there is much of a time difference between the two.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Portfolio Cloud*. Using *JIRA Portfolio Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JPOSERVER-1299].
  {panel}

I am missing a linking feature between the different hierarchies. Story and subtasks are (of course) correctly linked but the links "up" the hierarchy are missing.
That would help our developers to get to the source(hence the goal) of the tickets more easily.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Portfolio Cloud*. Using *JIRA Portfolio Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JPOSERVER-1834].
  {panel}

Plz watch attached screenshot. I think its very important when work in Kanban board, and need to change pirority in issues every day.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
